# ASP.NET Framework → ASP.NET Core 8 Migration

## Key Breaking Changes

| Framework Pattern | Core Replacement | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Response.End()` | **Removed entirely** — no equivalent | It called `Thread.Abort()` internally, which doesn't exist in .NET Core |
| `Response.Redirect(url, true)` | `return Redirect(url)` | No `endResponse` parameter; use action results instead |
| `Response.Clear/Write/AddHeader` | Return `IActionResult` types | Pipeline is middleware-based, not buffer-based |
| `ThreadAbortException` swallowing | **Delete it** | `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in Core |
| WebForms event handlers | Controller action methods | No page lifecycle or postback model |

## Migrated Code

```csharp
// ASP.NET Core 8 — MVC Controller
public class ReportController : Controller
{
    private readonly ILogger<ReportController> _logger;

    public ReportController(ILogger<ReportController> logger)
    {
        _logger = logger;
    }

    // POST /Report/Export
    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult Export()
    {
        var data = GenerateReport();

        // No Response.Clear/Write/End — return a result object instead.
        // The framework handles headers, content-type, and flushing.
        return File(
            Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(data),
            "text/csv",
            "report.csv"
        );
    }

    // POST /Report/Process
    [HttpPost]
    [Authorize]  // Replaces manual User.Identity.IsAuthenticated check
    public IActionResult Process()
    {
        try
        {
            ProcessRequest();
            return Redirect("/success");
        }
        catch (Exception ex)
        {
            _logger.LogError(ex, "Failed to process report");
            return Redirect("/error");
        }
    }
}
```

## Critical Pitfalls

**1. `Response.End()` will throw at runtime, not at compile time**
```csharp
// .NET 8 — compiles fine, EXPLODES at runtime
Response.Body.WriteAsync(...);  // works
HttpContext.Response.End();     // does not exist

// If you reference System.Threading.Thread.Abort():
Thread.Abort(); // throws PlatformNotSupportedException
```

**2. Don't recreate the old pattern with `HttpResponse`**
```csharp
// WRONG — fighting the framework
public async Task Export()
{
    Response.ContentType = "text/csv";
    Response.Headers.Append("Content-Disposition", "attachment; filename=report.csv");
    await Response.WriteAsync(data);
    await Response.CompleteAsync(); // NOT the same as Response.End()
}

// RIGHT — use action results
public IActionResult Export() => File(bytes, "text/csv", "report.csv");
```

**3. `[Authorize]` replaces manual auth checks**
```csharp
// Register in Program.cs
builder.Services.AddAuthentication(/* ... */);
builder.Services.AddAuthorization();

var app = builder.Build();
app.UseAuthentication();
app.UseAuthorization();  // order matters — must come after UseAuthentication
```

**4. `catch (ThreadAbortException)` — delete every instance**

Search your codebase and remove all `ThreadAbortException` catch blocks. In Core, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`, so the old catch clause would never fire and the real exception escapes unhandled.

## Quick Migration Checklist

```
✅ Replace Response.Write/End → return File(), Content(), Ok()
✅ Replace Response.Redirect(url, true) → return Redirect(url)
✅ Delete all catch (ThreadAbortException) blocks
✅ Replace manual auth checks → [Authorize] attribute
✅ Inject ILogger<T> instead of static LogError helpers
✅ Register auth middleware in correct order in Program.cs
✅ Target net8.0 in .csproj
```

The core mindset shift: **return results, don't mutate the response stream**. Framework controllers pushed bytes into a mutable `Response` buffer. Core controllers return `IActionResult` objects and let the middleware pipeline handle serialization.
